        <mxCell id="TysiPa89LfpG7-aD6HDz-53" value="• Internal Retrenchment is referred to as Turnaround Strategy. Focus here is on&lt;br&gt;improving efficiency.&lt;br&gt;• The aim is to cut cost, focus on reducing wasteful expenses, retrenchment of&lt;br&gt;&lt;div&gt;excess employees, etc. till the position of the firm improves. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;• There are certain conditions which suggest that turnaround needs to be adopted.&lt;br&gt;Continues Negative Cash flow Negative profits Declining Market Share Over staffing, High employee Turnover Noncompetitive products in portfolio Miss-Management&lt;br&gt;• The firm has to focus on the short and long-term needs.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The elements that contribute to turnaround are (a clear working plan should be&lt;br&gt;made with these things):&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &amp;gt;Changes in the top management&lt;br&gt;&amp;gt;Initial crediability-building actions&lt;br&gt; &amp;gt;Neutralizing external pressures&lt;br&gt; &amp;gt;Initial control&lt;br&gt; &amp;gt;Identifying quick payoff activities&lt;br&gt; &amp;gt;Quick cost reductions&lt;br&gt; &amp;gt;Revenue generation&lt;br&gt; &amp;gt;Asset liquidation for generating cash&lt;br&gt; &amp;gt;Move the goods or production where there are better working conditions.&lt;br&gt; &amp;gt;Better internal control&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;" style="rounded=0;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;" vertex="1" parent="tAh5_Dv9XLEUhuwZVZgv-8">
